< review>
Awesome pizza, but the place is not kid friendly. I haven't seen the band's so I can't comment on that. I went to the bar to get a drink and was told by the bartender to get in the "Order here" line which was full of lots of people trying to order pizza. Got to say this is the first bar I've ever been to you cannot order a beer at. So I left as the pizza was an hour and a half wait and I couldn't get a beer without waiting in line. They did have local enegren beer which is good. Ordered for pickup the next day and got it to go so I could try the pizza everyone said was so good. It did not disappoint. Also beware the hours vary almost everyday so I included a picture.<//review>

< text>
I've been here multiple times, at different times of the day (as well as different days of the week) and there was always a long wait. There is a pad of paper to put your name down, but not a good sense of how long the wait will be. The staff has given very low-ball estimates every time I asked. I was once told "about 15 minutes" over the phone but when I got there just minutes later, it was "maybe 45 minutes?"  I understand they are a business that relies on partly on walk-in clientele, so there is a need to keep prospective customers anchored at the shop, but this is frustrating if you can't get an accurate idea of how long you have to wait or when to come back.</text>

<rating>5< /rating>< review>
I LOVE FINDING THE CHEAPEST GAS IN CALIFORNIA and this place must have it. My sister lived in the sticks just north of Fresno in Madera County and I always filled up at Sunny's. Everyone that I have dealt with at this location has been so nice. I'm usually so excited about saving a million dollars on gas that I go inside and waste half a million on overpriced snacks...that's not a dig, I mean, gas station/liquor store snacks are always a rip-off, but it feels less terrible when you can fill your tank for almost nothin'!!! If you ever find yourself on Road 600, stop at Sunny and get gas...whether you need it or not!< /review>

<pics>None</pics>< Review>
I recently moved into the area and I decided it was time to find a salon. After reading yelp reviews I called to make an appt. but there was no answer. Vanessa called me back saying that she would be able to do my haircut and highlights. Today I went in for my 1:00 pm appt. with several pictures of different haircut ideas and I explained that I like to brighten my natural color with caramel low lights and some blond highlights, but not too heavy on the blond. After Vanessa finished my highlights, she rinsed my hair and then mentioned the need for a toner to tone down the blond.  When we got back to her chair I was pretty shocked at how blond my whole head was and how my natural hair color was pretty much gone. Though she was nice and tried to fix it by adding a darker color on top of the blond, it really didn't really make much of a change. I tried my best to make light of the situation, but when I got home and looked in the mirror I realized that I spent 5 hours in the chair and paid $125 (with the new client discount) for hair color that I'm not happy with.

I woke up the next morning and saw my hair in natural light. It looks kind of orange with some blond and the front of my hairline has a large crooked line where the color didn't get close enough to my roots. If I had seen it this way yesterday I would not have paid for the service. I contacted Vanessa to cancel the next appt. I made prior to seeing my hair like this and she said it "wasn't her problem" since I didn't throw a fit yesterday. Not only is she an unprofessional hairstylist, she doesn't know the first thing about customer service.< /Review>

I went here a month or two after it opened, so this review is at least one year after my visit. I have not been back after the disastrous first experience. To start, we were greeted by a young lady with very long hair (past her waist) and her hair looked dirty and greasy. This grossed out my wife but we went in anyway. After being seated, it took a while to get us menus. It took our waiter 10-15 minutes to get to us after that. He finslly showed up and we placed our orders. I asked specifically about the burrito I ordered and asked to get it with no rice. It then took over 30 minutes to get our order served. The waiter took off right after putting our plates on the table. I cut in to my burrito and you would think I ordered a rice burrito. It was supposed to be 'Surf and Turf', steak and shrimp. There was so little steak and even less shrimp. I couldn't believe it. When the waiter came over finally, I showed him the burrito and all he said is "I can place an order again for you." I reminded him that it took over 30 minutes to get what I got. He said sorry and I said forget it. Even though I didn't eat the burrito, I was charged for it. While the waiter apologized for the mistake, which is fine, the whole evening was filled with apologies for this and for that. I told him he shouldn't apologize so much because to us it didn't mean much. Other than a bad experience. My wife's food was very ordinary and nothing special. So I have not been back and probably never will return. There are too many other good choices to settle for this over priced place.</review>

< Review>
Been looking forward to trying this place and figured I‚Äôd go today and also pick up a plant for Mother‚Äôs day. Saw the sale sign and thought cool, I picked a good day!

Big mistake. At checkout, the cashier explained the sale only means more plants are out, but there‚Äôs no actual discount. The price tag is for the pot only. Plant cost separately. She asked twice if I was ok with the price, as though she knew she was ripping me off lol. Clearly she was, but I bought it anyway, knowing full well I would regret it later.

<rate>5</rate><Text>I‚Äôve walked by Yuko Kitchen so many times and I always tell myself that I need to check it out. Well I finally did and I‚Äôm pleasantly surprised with the quality of food that they serve. Their menu is a good size and they serve everything from juice with boba, sushi rolls, salads, bowls and dinner plates. I opted for the chicken plate which comes with teriyaki chicken, salad, spicy salmon roll, rice and a tasty treat for dessert. The chicken was good. I normally don‚Äôt like teriyaki but their sauce was pretty good and the chicken had a nice crisp to it. The salad dressing they use is pretty good and the spicy salmon roll was decent...it could have used a little bit more spice but I still enjoyed it. For $13 a plate, it‚Äôs such a good deal. The restaurant is also quite funky. Lots of plants which you can also purchase. Yuko Kitchen is one of those neighborhood mom and pop shops that adds charm to the area.<//Text>< Pictures>

<time>1615353327706<//time><Rating>5< /Rating><Review>You know those places you go sometimes and the moment you step inside the doors you are transported to another place. Yuko Kitchen is one of those places, nestled on the corner of downtown LA, that has always been a welcoming oasis in the midst of the chaotic downtown landscape. The food has always been consistent and healthy. The stand outs are the plates, rice bowls and daily specials for me. Cards and cash, street parking. Not so great service, but just good enough not to lose a star. Unfiltered saki and hot udon noodle were had, and both were great. <pics>None<//pics><review>Favorite go-to takeout place in DTLA. The bowlitos are wonderful, like big sushi rolls in the shape of burritos. The rolls are excellent: innovative, and the ingredients always taste super fresh. I usually get the Mermaid roll, a Salmon roll served UNDER a bed of salad with delicious house made roasted garlic slices (they include a cup of them on the side with the takeout orders). The sodas are delicious, I like the strawberry lemonade (fresh squeezed lemons, fresh strawberry puree), and have them add boba. The desserts- cookies, cupcakes, and whoopie pies- are as adorable as they are delicious. The girls behind the counter are polite and professional and they have literally the cleanest kitchen I've ever seen.</review>< Name>

<Name>Kate Scherer</Name><time>1487815657883<//time><rating>5<//rating><Text>I used to frequent the original location on a daily basis when my office was across the street in Miracle Mile and I begged Yuko to open a downtown location when we moved. I could easily eat here everyday. It's reasonable, delicious & healthy (if you can stay away from her amazing desserts.)

I love the homemade soups (curry soup is #1) and sashimi salads. The bowls if you want something heartier (garlic shrimp bowl!). I also love the sides (pickled radishes, and the tomato + roasted garlic salad). The mint lemonade is another memorable must-have.

The desserts are really the highlight. The choco-san (flourless chocolate cookies with homemade whip inside), the cream babies (so fluffy they melt in your mouth), even her chocolate chip cookies are special (thick and doughey with big chunks of chocolate). There is always something new and everything is insanely good.</Text>< Pics>

<text>Armando made this such a great experience! I brought in a rough image of what I wanted my tattoo to look like and he was able to copy it down and make it PERFECT.
A couple things I thought were strange, though, were that 1) I wasn't asked to sign a waiver or anything before my appointment and 2) I wasn't given a bandage or a gauze pad or anything once my tattoo was done. This was a solid black tattoo so it was definitely tender after it was finished. It was pretty hard to drive home with my shirt rubbing against it the whole way and, when i got home, i could see that there was a bunch of dried blood around it. Luckily I happened to have a big enough gauze patch to cover it at home.
The facilities are really nice, really comfortable seats in the waiting area, clean work spaces, clean restrooms, a good full-length mirror. There was a TV playing some movies while i was there and it helped to have some entertainment to distract from the sting of the needle (my fourth tattoo and i'm still not completely used to it!).
Overall, a great trip! Just wish there was more explanation of aftercare at the end of my visit.<//text>< pics>

< Review>
Wait here is very long. We were a party of 11, so we tried to call them to make a reservation but they put us on hold and left us hanging like that. We just went ahead and considered walking in.  Fell in line but when the receptionist knew that we were a party of 11 without reservation, she told us that she's not sure if they can accommodate such a  large number of people in one group and told us we have to get out of the line because she would have to talk to her manager.  We went to the side and she went ahead to sit the groups behind us without calling the manager.  Not until we made a follow-up did she radio the manager and that's when he talked to us and gave us an approximate time of when we can be seated.  It took more than an hour (approx 30min more of what was promised) and we were still seated in different tables. We were the only ones left in their waiting area. Their process could be improved.
The food is just ok, most of it were salty.  The onion flower and the grilled shrimp was salty and oily. The slab of ribs could be more tender and it tasted like the sauce was not cooked and was just placed on top after reheating the ribs.
Waiters were nice though.< /Review>

['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNo-JbLLGnAymp6P6-6w_GrhtsLMMHUtWhHaTsn=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics>
<name>Kelly Bezz<//name><Rating>5< /Rating><Date>1537140099727<//Date>< Text>
Texas Roadhouse is a family steakhouse. There is easy on/off access to I-80 E and W. They have their own butcher on premises. The theme of the restaurant is of course Texas although they have lots of local mementos. The waiters/waitresses are usually very friendly and courteous. They come by often to make sure your order is correct but not too often to be intrusive. Texas Roadhouse offers a full bar and seating in the bar. Booths and tables fill the rest of the floor. They offer high chairs and will remove a chair for if you are in a wheelchair. Country music is played-rather loudly but not too loud. It is not that easy to carry on intimate or family conversation here but the food is all delicious and so the trade off is worth it!  While looking over your menu and waiting for your food, they offer a bucket with peanuts in the shell and a refuse bucket. They have great rolls with cinnamon butter (although regular butter is available upon request) that melt in your mouth. Their steaks are cooked to order to perfection. They usually offer some seafood like shrimp too. In addition to bar beverages they offer soft drinks and water. They offer appetizers (their blooming onion is delicious!) and if you can handle it even dessert. Most people cannot finish the large portions and Texas Roadhouse has a nice box for you to take home your leftovers (and they didn‚Äôt even charge us for the bag in which to put all our leftovers!). There is a handicapped accessible parking out front and handicapped accessible bathrooms in the back of the restaurant. You can call ahead and do quite a bit of your waiting for a table at home if you desire. There is usually a wait at meal times. They also have an app with which you can ask for a table. They do offer take-out if you call and order (or order inside and wait, or use the app) and pickup at the front main desk.  For tourists and t-shirt collectors you may purchase a Texas Roadhouse T shirt for $10 at the front or ask your waitress/waiter. I highly recommend Texas Roadhouse for a delicious steak!< /Text>

< review>
Seriously, best steak ever. They get it right the first try! Logan's and outback can't do that for some reason. The only down fall is the yeast rolls... I'm trying to stay keto and yeast rolls are not keto... Ugh so hard to resist!!! They melt in your mouth. Anyway, back on topic... We always get the 20 oz ribeye and split it, getting 2 side salads as the sides that come with meal. It makes two 10-oz ribeye meals for us to enjoy for around $35 after tip! Can't beat that price! Between the steak, salad and biscuits ( which I cannot resist) we always walk away stuffed! There just aren't with Texas Roadhouse in the world..... OH!! Also, veterans discount if you are a vet. It varies from store to store but we've gotten as much as 25% from them. <review>We will not be returning. In the past, we would try to get in, but the wait would always be way too long. This time we called ahead. This was supposed to shave 30 min off the estimated 45 minute wait. We still ended up waiting 30 minutes or so. The waiting area is crowded and dirty (or maybe it's peanut shells on the floor - looks dirty to me). The place is so loud the servers have to yell, and you still can't hear them. It was even louder in the dining area. The rolls are soft and chewy, not in a good way. The food took forever to come. My wife said the ribs tasted boiled, daughter said her medium-rare steak was medium, and mine seemed to be mostly fat. <Rating>3< /Rating>< Text>
Great food, great prices and a very playful atmosphere combine at Texas roadhouse to create a unique dining experience. Feel free to their those peanut shells on the floor. Don't mind the wait staff as they line dance in the aisles. Food quality consistency is something I've come to expect here. The prime rib especially is always worth the purchase. The take out is also great. I usually get one of the $9.99 plates and rarely finish everything in one sitting.

Update: Togo ordering has been very poor here lately.  The last 3 times I've come in they've either forgotten I was waiting for my for after paying or it took twice as long as quoted for the food to be ready. Waiting over an hour for a phone in order to be ready is just unacceptable.<//Text>

<text>I'm a vegetarian. Our waitress, Ms. Franny , bent over backward to make sure nothing I ordered had meat products or meat broth. Which means she went back and forth to the kitchen multiple times, checking and double checking that everything was okay for me to eat. When she got to the point that my options were incredibly limited (I ordered the Country Veg dish, that allows for 4 side dishes, only one salad allowed, but only 3 were okay), Ms. Franny brought over the manager, Cassie. Cassie went over all the facts and different options, including the fact that when things are busy (as was the case, it was a 35 wait to seat 3), they fry the French fries in the same oil as the fish. She mentioned microwaving a potato since baking it would take 45 minutes. I jumped at the opportunity. <UserId.>113410571155809539983</UserId.><Name>Gina</Name><Time>1519526482595</Time><rating>5< /rating><Text>Friendly staff make sure you call ahead for seating otherwise you'll be stuck there an hour or so waiting .
They have bar seating , lots of fun frozen drinks . If you the sangrita make sure you have a ride home ! oh boy that's a strong one you don't even need the kicker .
The steaks are amazing ! LOVE the sweet potatoes smothered in marshmallows brown sugar and butter . My kids like the chili . Best steak fries in town . We like to add the texas signature steak sauce with their Ranch for dipping the steak fries . The prime rib is unbelievable . They have incredible real au jus sauce not that fake stuff they usually have at most restaurants . We've never had their barbecue chicken but we hear it's good. The salmon is very tasty awesome tartar sauce .  It's really loud so be prepared for cheering and screaming and hollering at people's birthdays . Loud music loud people loud staff crowded as can be , if you get there really early you can avoid the crowds . Good food ... One thing that really sucks their bowls smell like WET DOG . If you get a salad I recommend asking for a plate or to go box . All their salads come pre-prepared with a boiled egg on the side they take off the egg if you don't want it . Which I believe they shouldn't put the egg on the salad unless it's ordered because the egg residue will sit in the lettuce and tomatoes and cheese and the residue was still on the food . And if you mention the smell of the bowls you get nasty looks from the staff . I don't bother ordering salads or ice cream anymore . The ice cream bowls are the same bowls they use for the salads . To avoid the wet dog smell , order your ice cream in a cup or to-go box . I Googled wet dog smell on plates and Google says it's because of old egg residue stained into the plate . Other then that this place has great food .</Text>< Pics>
